text: couple of things we've discussed before, maybe in slightly different ways. So first, I really do think that we've learned over time the importance of focus. Maybe there were times going back years ago that we didn't have as much focus as we could have. And it's natural, I think, in a research organization to fall prey to that because there are so many interesting ideas that you can explore at any point in time. And it's easy to get distracted by whatever the latest shiny object is. I think it can be exacerbated if the leadership of the organization are throwing out questions to the team without appreciating the effort it takes to answer those questions. And so that's generally with good intentions. I mean, there are a lot of good ideas out there, but I think it's important to make sure that we stay focused, that we don't lose sight of the priorities in front of us. And I think that we've probably learned over time more how to do that. The other thing I would mention is in terms of that peer review process. I mean, that's something that has evolved a lot over time. And during the early days when we put it in, going back to, say, the late 2000s, the process was pretty overly formalized and it got pretty ridiculous. And I think that's something that we need to be doing. And I think that's something rigid at a certain point where there were checklists of these are all the steps in the process. And I think what we found is that's overly rigid and that no two reviews are alike. You need to be able to evolve the process to meet the needs of any particular project you've got. So I think we found that it's better to be a little more nimble with that while still having some overall structure.
